      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm working on my dissertation and i keep hitting a wall with my p-values. if i get a p-value of 0.06, why is it technically \"not significant\" even if the effect size looks pretty big? it feels like the math is ignoring the trend.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06 is technically \"not significant\" because it exceeds the conventional alpha level, which is usually set at 0.05. This threshold dictates the risk you are willing to take of rejecting a true null hypothesis (a Type I error). While a large effect size suggests a real relationship, the p-value tells you the probability of observing that data *if* no real effect existed, and 0.06 is just slightly too high for your chosen cutoff. It's important to distinguish between statistical significance and practical significance.",
      "source": "target",
